## Basic Usage

### Example 1.1: Simple CSV Parsing

```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

const csv = `product,price,stock
Widget A,19.99,100
Widget B,29.99,50
Widget C,9.99,200`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.headers);
// ["product", "price", "stock"]

console.log(result.rows);
// [
//   { product: "Widget A", price: 19.99, stock: 100 },
//   { product: "Widget B", price: 29.99, stock: 50 },
//   { product: "Widget C", price: 9.99, stock: 200 }
// ]

// Access specific row
const firstRow = result.rows[0];
console.log(`Product: ${firstRow.product}, Price: $${firstRow.price}`);
// Product: Widget A, Price: $19.99
```

### Example 1.2: Handling CSV with Quoted Fields

```typescript
const csv = `company,description,founded
TechCorp,"Develops software, cloud solutions",2010
InnovateLabs,"AI, Machine Learning, Big Data",2015
DataWorks,"Specializes in data processing, analytics",2012`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Commas inside quotes are preserved
console.log(result.rows[0].description);
// "Develops software, cloud solutions"

// Can safely display without parsing issues
result.rows.forEach(company => {
  console.log(`${company.company}: ${company.description}`);
});
```

### Example 1.3: Working with Null and Coerced Values

```typescript
const csv = `id,name,salary,active,notes
1,Alice,75000.50,true,
2,Bob,null,false,On leave
3,Charlie,85000,null,`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

result.rows.forEach(employee => {
  const salary = employee.salary ?? "Not specified";
  const status = employee.active ? "Active" : "Inactive";

  console.log(`${employee.name}: ${salary} (${status})`);
});
// Alice: 75000.5 (Active)
// Bob: Not specified (Inactive)
// Charlie: 85000 (Inactive)
```

