# CSV Parser - Usage Examples

This document provides practical examples for using the CSV Parser library in various scenarios.

## Table of Contents

1. [Basic Usage](#basic-usage)
2. [Data Analysis](#data-analysis)
3. [Data Cleaning](#data-cleaning)
4. [Business Reporting](#business-reporting)
5. [Advanced Filtering](#advanced-filtering)
6. [Error Handling](#error-handling)
7. [Custom Formats](#custom-formats)

---

## Basic Usage

### Example 1.1: Simple CSV Parsing

```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

const csv = `product,price,stock
Widget A,19.99,100
Widget B,29.99,50
Widget C,9.99,200`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.headers);
// ["product", "price", "stock"]

console.log(result.rows);
// [
//   { product: "Widget A", price: 19.99, stock: 100 },
//   { product: "Widget B", price: 29.99, stock: 50 },
//   { product: "Widget C", price: 9.99, stock: 200 }
// ]

// Access specific row
const firstRow = result.rows[0];
console.log(`Product: ${firstRow.product}, Price: $${firstRow.price}`);
// Product: Widget A, Price: $19.99
```

### Example 1.2: Handling CSV with Quoted Fields

```typescript
const csv = `company,description,founded
TechCorp,"Develops software, cloud solutions",2010
InnovateLabs,"AI, Machine Learning, Big Data",2015
DataWorks,"Specializes in data processing, analytics",2012`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Commas inside quotes are preserved
console.log(result.rows[0].description);
// "Develops software, cloud solutions"

// Can safely display without parsing issues
result.rows.forEach(company => {
  console.log(`${company.company}: ${company.description}`);
});
```

### Example 1.3: Working with Null and Coerced Values

```typescript
const csv = `id,name,salary,active,notes
1,Alice,75000.50,true,
2,Bob,null,false,On leave
3,Charlie,85000,null,`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

result.rows.forEach(employee => {
  const salary = employee.salary ?? "Not specified";
  const status = employee.active ? "Active" : "Inactive";

  console.log(`${employee.name}: ${salary} (${status})`);
});
// Alice: 75000.5 (Active)
// Bob: Not specified (Inactive)
// Charlie: 85000 (Inactive)
```

---

## Data Analysis

### Example 2.1: Sales Data Analysis

```typescript
const salesCSV = `date,product,quantity,unitPrice,region
2024-01-15,ProductA,100,25.50,North
2024-01-15,ProductB,50,15.00,South
2024-01-16,ProductA,75,25.50,East
2024-01-16,ProductC,200,8.50,West
2024-01-17,ProductA,120,25.50,North
2024-01-17,ProductB,80,15.00,East`;

const result = parseCSV(salesCSV);

// Calculate total revenue per product
const byProduct = result.groupBy("product");

for (const [product, sales] of byProduct) {
  const revenue = sales.reduce((sum, s) => 
    sum + (s.quantity * s.unitPrice), 0
  );
  console.log(`${product}: $${revenue.toFixed(2)}`);
}
// ProductA: $9382.50
// ProductB: $2200.00
// ProductC: $1700.00

// Find top performing region
const byRegion = result.groupBy("region");
let topRegion = { name: "", total: 0 };

for (const [region, sales] of byRegion) {
  const total = sales.reduce((sum, s) => 
    sum + (s.quantity * s.unitPrice), 0
  );
  if (total > topRegion.total) {
    topRegion = { name: region, total };
  }
}

console.log(`Top region: ${topRegion.name} ($${topRegion.total.toFixed(2)})`);
// Top region: North ($5890.00)
```

### Example 2.2: Student Grades Analysis

```typescript
const gradesCSV = `student,math,science,english,history
Alice,95,92,88,90
Bob,87,85,90,88
Charlie,92,94,91,93
Diana,78,81,79,82
Eve,98,96,99,97`;

const result = parseCSV(gradesCSV);

// Calculate average grade per subject
const subjects = ["math", "science", "english", "history"];
const averages = {};

for (const subject of subjects) {
  averages[subject] = result.average(subject);
}

console.log("Subject Averages:");
for (const [subject, avg] of Object.entries(averages)) {
  console.log(`${subject}: ${avg.toFixed(1)}`);
}
// Subject Averages:
// math: 90.0
// science: 89.6
// english: 89.4
// history: 90.0

// Find students with perfect attendance (all grades >= 90)
const topStudents = result.filter(row => 
  subjects.every(subject => row[subject] >= 90)
);

console.log(`Students with 90+ in all subjects: ${topStudents.count()}`);
// Students with 90+ in all subjects: 2

topStudents.rows.forEach(student => {
  console.log(`- ${student.student}`);
});
// - Alice
// - Eve
```

### Example 2.3: Temperature Data Analysis

```typescript
const tempCSV = `date,location,temperature,humidity,precipitation
2024-01-15,Station A,32.5,65,0.2
2024-01-15,Station B,35.2,58,0
2024-01-16,Station A,33.1,68,0.5
2024-01-16,Station B,36.8,52,0
2024-01-17,Station A,31.9,70,1.2
2024-01-17,Station B,34.5,60,0.3`;

const result = parseCSV(tempCSV);

// Average temperature by location
const byLocation = result.groupBy("location");

for (const [location, readings] of byLocation) {
  const avgTemp = readings.reduce((sum, r) => sum + r.temperature, 0) 
                   / readings.length;
  console.log(`${location}: ${avgTemp.toFixed(1)}В°C`);
}
// Station A: 32.5В°C
// Station B: 35.5В°C

// Days with precipitation
const withRain = result.filter(row => row.precipitation > 0);
console.log(`Days with precipitation: ${withRain.count()} out of ${result.count()}`);
// Days with precipitation: 3 out of 6
```

